Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code for your `TimedExecutor`.

## Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Swallow abort | Remove entirely |

## Why It Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports preemptive thread termination. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** where the work voluntarily checks a `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the token for cancellation to be effective.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in modern .NET.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work must receive a token to cooperate with cancellation |
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Task-based model is preferred; threads are pooled |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Timer-based cancellation replaces join+abort |
| `thread.Abort()` | Automatic via `cts.CancelAfter` | Token signals cancellation; no forced termination |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No abort to reset — cancellation is voluntary |
| Manual `error` variable | Exception propagates naturally | `Task.Run` marshals exceptions automatically |

## Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE — .NET Framework
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(data),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER — .NET 8
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        // Check the token at regular checkpoints
        foreach (var item in data)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            Process(item);
        }
        return ComputeResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is not instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token only works at checkpoints. If `work` does a 60-second blocking call without checking the token, the timeout is ineffective until that call returns. |
| **Must pass token through the full chain** | Every method in the call chain must accept and forward the `CancellationToken`. One method that ignores it breaks the whole chain. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures only *your* timeout triggers the catch — not an unrelated upstream cancellation. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It holds an internal timer. The `using` statement prevents leaks. The original code had no equivalent concern. |
| **Uncooperative code can't be cancelled** | If you call a third-party library that doesn't accept a token (e.g., a long-running native call), move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` as a last resort. `Task.Run` without token checks will let the work finish in the background even after timeout. |
| **`Task.Run` captures `SynchronizationContext`** | In UI apps, be aware of deadlocks with `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`. Prefer the async overload. |
